The National Association for the Benefit of Colour People (NAACP) has published warnings for colour people traveling to Missouri on the basis of discriminatory principles of the state and racist attacks.
“The NAACP Travel Recommendation for the State of Missouri, with effect from August 28, 2017, calls on African-American passengers, visitors and inhabitants of Missouri to pay more attention when traveling across the country as a result of a series of controversial racial-motivated incidents that are currently occurring throughout the country,” the association said in a statement.
The NAACP said that this step was taken on the basis of current Missouri laws that facilitate the defense of racist-motivated acts in court, as well as the result of the actions of criminal proceedings that are disproportionately targeting minorities.
“There is a violation of civil rights.
People are arrested by the police only because of their skin color, they are attacked or killed,” said for Kansas City Star NAACP president for Missouri Rod Chapel.
“We’re getting the greatest number of complaints.”
This is the first warning of its kind that the organization issued to the state of the United States.
Among the incidents the organization cited were racial-motivated harassment against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in controversial circumstances earlier this year after he had a gasoline in his journey across the state and was arrested by police without accusation of committing a crime.
The Travel Recommendation also highlights a recent statement by the Missouri State Supreme Prosecutor's Office, which states that black drivers are 75% more likely to be stopped by the police.
“The purpose of the travel recommendation is to warn people and warn their families, friends and colleagues of what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People must be prepared – they should carry the money to pay the guarantee or warn their relatives that they are going to travel through the state.”
According to the current figures of the FBI program to report hatred acts, there were a hundred cases of hatred behavior in Missouri in 2015, bringing the state to the 16th place among all states.
The travel warning is also a response to the new Missouri law that facilitates the complaint for discrimination in providing accommodation or employment.
The American Union for Civil Liberties (ACLU) issued a travel recommendation for Texas and Arizona after the states approved an immigration law that allows government officials to arrest people on the basis of a violation of this law, which according to ACLU is intended to improve racial profiling.
Travel recommendations are usually issued by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs for foreign countries, but recently lawyer groups have applied to these measures in response to specific laws and trends within the United States.
