Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start receiving patients. Other clinics will join in October and will be fully implemented throughout England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a HIV drug administered before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among the endangered patients.
Application of PrEP before sex means that a sufficient amount of specific medications is found in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
The patients tested include homosexual or bisexual men, transgender people and HIV-positive partners who are not treated successfully.
Clinics shall identify eligible participants who sign consent to participate in the test, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by the appropriate treatment.
People living and registered at the GP in the UK can also register at their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in the test.
The program will come taxpayers at £10 million and NHS England has signed this week a deal to distribute drugs after obtaining an international public procurement.
The trial period is designed to collect clinical evidence and evaluate the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: ‘This important intervention should complement and fully take advantage of the ever-growing and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It’s another milestone in more than thirty years’ efforts to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.”
Deborah Gold, Executive Director of NAT (National Aids Trust), said: “We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and patients in danger, it will offer the possibility of transition of the English HIV epidemic.
From September, NSH will offer patients exposed to a high risk of HIV infection a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and is not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will lead to improved quality of many lives.
We are pleased to accept this statement.”
Ian Green, Chief Executive Officer of Terrence Higgins Trust said: ‘Priority number one must be the rapid implementation of tests throughout the country; we must ensure its availability to every patient.
