Startups that will help your company not become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the satisfaction of employees of her e-commerce startup, but did not find the appropriate survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even misleading.
And despite promising the anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their confidence in the whole process.
“I was looking for consistency and objectivity,” said Errett, owner of the e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed based in San Francisco, which employs 75 people.
He asked for help from the outside.
New human resource startups are constantly emerging on the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
Through the creation and licensing of software with a specific intention of measuring employees’ duties, startups enable companies to conduct quick voting, target specific teams and demographic groups, further offering full anonymity of employees and a hot line for complaints, and in some cases also enable informers to circumvent the top and contact the director directly.
“There are tools on the market like Diet and Fitbit that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of the Glint startup based in Reedwood City.
Errett said that thanks to Glinta, she gained greater awareness of what her employees think and feel in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and the voting of specific teams, Glint offers the company’s temperature map and an overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as a overview of managers with low ratings – allowing the user to work on the correction.
Companies begin to realize that it is necessary to pay attention to the culture of the work environment - for the event that they would become another Uber - which is melting in scandals after the former employee posted a post on his blog describing the corporate environment and disturbing employees who dare to speak openly.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture research is a profitable business opportunity.
According to the website Let's Talk Payments, which deals with technical and financial advances, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance sector could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
Startup Convercent from Denver, Colorado, which helps companies in prevention and detection of inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before the Uber scandals.
Among the 600 customers of Convercent are Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber has recently taken its wings.
Similar to Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable “black” surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hot line that allows employees to report unsuitable behavior.
If the Director-General is involved in the problem, complaints are sent directly to the Board of Directors.
“The Court of Public Opinion has authorized regulators,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of the Convercent startup.
If a company is convicted of misconduct with its employees or unethical behavior - and if the regulators do not step forward - it may face expensive consequences due to customer boycott, employee exhaust or judicial proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs more than 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to raise employees’ awareness of corporate policies and procedures and ensure a easy way to contact corporate management.
Earlier, if the employee wanted to report any problem, he had to search for the telephone number or e-mail to the company’s management, officially submit a complaint and hope for a successful solution.
It was often a frightening and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday’s Chief Executive Officer, that there was no reliable way to track employees’ complaints before.
Now that the company uses Convercent, it is secured to quickly detect and solve problems that have never before reached managers sitting in offices, miles away from real complaints solving - for example, discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
“It’s close to a holistic, overall view of the staff’s experience,” said Vitrano, who manages the Ruby Tuesday risk management group.
At the same time, we protect shareholders from legal disputes by employees.”
Companies ceased to take ethics, values and employee participation to light weight in 2002 after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after Enron's fall in the matter of employee ethical rights abuse, Quinlan said.
But only when the “social media” began to realize that in the online world they can’t simply hide their bone marrow in the closet.
“Before people started using ethics to track technology, they relied on faith,” Quinlan added.
Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity approved by courageous capital investors who have supported both startups.
Convercent picked up a total of $10 million from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital as part of its February campaign and eventually took up $47 million capital.
Glint earned $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and earned $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising due to the mutual nature of societies, culture and risk capital.
The growing number of research clearly confirms that today’s employees expect from their workplace more than ever before.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are not the main advantage.
Employees want to realize that they are accepted and appreciated and that they spend their time in a company that seeks a positive mission.
“When people are happy in their work, they realize that their voice is heard and that their work is rewarding, they strive for the company’s success,” said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employment benefits of LinkedIn, which uses Convercent and Glint.
Investors earn if companies are successful and companies prosper if their employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool appears on the market to ensure employees’ commitment and commitment to the company, it is no wonder that there will be a lot of investors who will support this effort.
According to work culture experts, it is important to have data about employees’ satisfaction.
But the data itself is ineffective unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The fact is that once a company requires feedback from its employees, there can be major changes.
And if the change does not happen quickly - in the worst case at all - it can cause disappointment and disinterest of employees.
“When you’re asking for 4,000 opinions, you’ll have to be prepared for 4,000 conversations,” said Russell Raath, consulting director at Kotter International, who was a witness to many companies that too much relied on the data itself.
“Because as soon as you do not reach the end, the employees begin to ask themselves the question: ‘Have they heard me at all?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, then why should it interest me?”
Madison Reed, which is now conducting regularly every month surveys among employees, can tackle Glinta to solve the problem within one day, Errett said.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated by slow decision-making and communication quality, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and start communication training to successfully solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday gets a very important look at its employees and hopes that in the long run it will high employment in a industry known for its frequent dismissals.
“If you don’t strive to create a transparent working environment, employees will not trust you,” Vitrano added.
And once you start losing employees, you lose customers.
And with the flow of customers, the whole company is bankrupt.”
