Facebook plans to further check facts to limit the number of fake messages
Facebook will send more potentially fake articles to third parties to check and display findings under the original posts in an effort to fight the so-called “fake news,” the largest social network said on Thursday.
In a statement on its website, the company writes that it will start using updated machine learning to detect possible hoaxs, which will be sent to third parties to verify and potentially display the survey results under the original posts.
Facebook has been described as one of the main sources of fake news and many believe that these unconfirmed news have affected the last year’s U.S. presidential election.
French voters are flooded by the lavines of fake news about the May presidential elections and Germany plans to impose a penalty on the social media network before the September elections if they do not remove angry posts quickly.
In a statement released in Germany on Thursday, Facebook said it is planning to test a new fake news control feature in the US, France, the Netherlands and Germany.
“In addition to displaying reports verified by third parties, people ask for more content to be better informed and to be able to make the right decisions about what they can share,” said Sara Su, Facebook’s product news manager.
She added that Facebook continues to test the “related articles” feature and is also working on further changes to reduce the number of fake messages.
Creation of a graphic novel: A Castle in England
The small castle Scotney Castle recently played a major role in the music video of the Squeeze group and found its shelter in it by Margaret Thatcher during the 1970s and 1980s.
Scotney, however, was a witness from his comfortable place near the Bewl River in Kent, Britain, to 700 years of stormy history that inspired the curved Jamie Rhodes of the York County – known for his interest in historical documents – to create a graphic novel.
“The sight of a man who is 300 years after his death fascinates me,” says Rhodes with a serious face.
“When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection.”
The graphic novel A Castle in England documentes the lives of families who lived in the Castle of Scotney from the Middle Ages to the Eduard period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
But it’s not the first Rhodes’ book inspired by the archives: it’s also the author of Dead Men’s Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by the British Library’s documents – a project that was very emotional for him.
“I was fascinated by the fingerprint on the letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jacobites,” he said.
“This is his fingerprint.
And the letters always smell like smoke, because at that time you had to burn a candle to read.
When I get to the letter now, 300 years later, it’s like I’m back in time.
I love the archives!”
For someone who is so fascinated by the old papers, the support from the National Trust and Arts Council England and the possibility of staying in the castle for four months is almost a dream.
Rhodes spent time exploring the Victorian “new” castle, browsing the archives, and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of the hyena on the wall and the bottles that have been thrown for centuries in the hole.
He walked through the land and explored the ruins of the old castle, talked with the hats, gardeners and sometimes also with the artists who worked on illustrations to his book.
In the evening, he “dry whiskey and wrote.”
Scotney's confidential history is relatively large unknown, as the National Trust only gained access to the documents in 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived at the site ten years later, the employees just began to penetrate the archives that Rhodes described in words, as if “the aristocrats of many centuries are throwing their hands with the words, ‘Take it into the roof.’”
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing the property: “You may think that the dispute about the land is boring,” Rhodes said, “but I’ve met one case when two families struggled about the bridge.
Let the people go!”
Some stories in the book use the castle as a reflection bridge and go deeper into English history, including the story called The Labourer, who follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English uprising in 1381.
“I found a record of the 1380 castle rebellion, which was in a book called Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex,” Rhodes said.
“The English rebellion actually started in this area and I thought that the rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe it’s somewhat connected.”
Other stories are closely linked to the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest, which was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about a 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly filmed his own funeral when he filled the roof of stones (which was discovered up to a few years after the roof was discovered).
Rhodes' favourite family is Darrell's: "I was interested in the male generation - the men at that time were always in debt and spent money on things they couldn't afford.
Different generations of the Darrell family resolved this by marrying wealthy or old gentlemen—I imagine they were beautiful gentlemen who liked the heads of the inheritors.”
With the end of his stay in the castle, Rhodes is looking for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week station in the Finnish wilderness, where he inspired his next book about Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century, which was absorbed by nature.
This is a special place for Scotney.
“I was sad when I left,” he said.
“I said to myself, ‘Now I want to go back to real life.’”
