“I wanted to make sure you are aware of such a significant event,” HMX-1 commander wrote in an e-mail to his supreme, the representative commander of the Navy for Aviation day before the event began.
The report suggested that the helicopter will arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at about 7:00 p.m. on the occasion of the show, which is scheduled to start at 15:00 p.m. and will remain on the site until the full cleaning of the entire place, which was scheduled between 18:00 and 21:00 p.m.
The e-mail also stated that if there is a delay in the departure from the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for the return flight due to the working hours regulations.
The original crew remained on the site that evening along with the helicopter and together with them a security unit.
From the records - obtained by the TIME Weekly - it was not clear if the second crew was finally sent.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government assets for political purposes.
