The flight to the Made in America show was part of the current crew training, the state official said.
The helicopter unit on the same day landed another eleven hours as part of the “non-Presidential support missions”.
The White House said there were no additional revenues paid from the taxpayers’ money.
The spokesman Sikorsky said the company was in no way interested in negotiations on the exposure of a helicopter to South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights and the accurate cost related to the show is hard to determine according to the maritime statement.
According to the Ministry of Defense, the hour price for the fiscal year 2017 is $24 380 per flight hour.
The unit records indicate the time of 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are significantly below that amount.
“Telling the costs of taxpayers on the basis of estimates for expenditure refunds is very misleading,” said Walters.
“These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in annual costs.”
According to a 2015 RAND study, DoD expenditure refunds do not include cost per person, but include fuel price, maintenance and contractual costs.
The White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of a helicopter for the purposes of the show.
“The idea of the show that takes place this week is to introduce products manufactured in the US,” Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of contributing to the defense of our country, and of providing jobs to hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other military equipment, in the production of which countless American citizens are involved.
